'''Daniel Thomas Meyer''' (born August 3, 1952 in [[Hamilton, Ohio]]) is a retired [[professional baseball]] player whose career spanned 15 seasons, 12 of which were played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) with the [[Detroit Tigers]] (1974<U+2013>76), the [[Seattle Mariners]] (1977<U+2013>81), and the [[Oakland Athletics]] (1982<U+2013>85). Meyer primarily played [[first baseman|first base]], but also played [[left fielder|left field]], [[third baseman|third base]], [[right fielder|right field]], and [[center fielder|center field]]. He batted [[left-handed]] while throwing [[right-handed]]. During his playing career, Meyer was listed at {{convert|5|ft|11|in|cm}} and weighed {{convert|180|lb|kg}}.

After attending the [[University of Arizona]] and [[Santa Ana College]], Meyer was drafted by the Detroit Tigers during the [[1972 Major League Baseball Draft]]. He began his career in the [[minor league baseball|minor leagues]] with the [[Bristol Tigers]]. Meyer made his major league debut in 1974. Over his career in the majors, Meyer compiled a .253 [[batting average]] with 411 [[runs scored]], 944 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 153 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], 31 [[triple (baseball)|triples]], 86 [[home run]]s, and 459 [[run batted in|runs batted in]] (RBIs) in 1,118 [[games played]].

==Early life==
Meyer was born on August 3, 1952 in [[Hamilton, Ohio]]. He attended [[Mater Dei High School (Santa Ana, California)|Mater Dei High School]] in [[Santa Ana, California]]. In 1970, Meyer was inducted into the school's baseball [[hall of fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Baseball: Hall of Fame|url=http://www.materdei.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=66352&type=d&termREC_ID=&pREC_ID=148093|work=Mater Dei High School Athletics|publisher=Mater Dei High School|accessdate=21 November 2010}}</ref> Meyer spent one year (1971) at the University of Arizona.<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Arizona Wildcats (Tucson, AZ)|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/schools/arizona.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> In 1972, Meyer enrolled in [[Santa Ana College]] where he played [[second baseman|second base]] on the school's baseball team.<ref>{{cite web|title=MLB Amateur Draft Picks who came from "Santa Ana College (Santa Ana, CA)"|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/index.cgi?exact=1&came_from=Santa%20Ana%20College%20(Santa%20Ana,%20CA)&exact=1&query_type=came_from|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> He was selected by the [[Detroit Tigers]] during the fourth round of the [[1972 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=4th Round of the 1972 MLB June Amateur Draft |url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?query_type=year_round&year_ID=1972&draft_round=4&draft_type=junreg|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref>

==Professional career==
===Detroit Tigers===
In 1972, at the age of 19, Meyer made his [[professional baseball]] debut in the [[Detroit Tigers]] [[minor league baseball|minor league]] organization. He was assigned to play with the [[Bristol Tigers]] of the [[Minor league baseball#Rookie|rookie-level]] [[Appalachian League]], where he [[batting average|batted]] .396 with 93 hits, 11 doubles, six triples, and 14 home runs in 65 [[games played]]. On defense, he played [[second baseman|second]] and [[third baseman|third base]]. He led the league in batting average, hits, and [[total bases]] (158) that season.<ref>{{cite web|title=1972 Appalachian League Batting Leaders|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=10261&sort_by=TB|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> During his second professional season in 1973, Meyer was assigned to the [[Lakeland Tigers]] of the [[Minor league baseball#Class A|Class-A]] [[Florida State League]]. With Lakeland, he batted .241 with 114 hits, 17 doubles, six triples, and 10 home runs in 133 games played. In the field, Meyer only played second base. It would later prove to be his last professional season playing at that position.

Meyer began the 1974 season in the minor leagues with the [[Evansville Triplets]] of the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]]. In 129 games with the Triplets, he batted .302 with 75 [[runs scored]], 146 hits, 26 doubles, seven triples, nine home runs, 57 RBIs, and 10 [[stolen base]]s. Meyer was a [[September call-up]] for the Detroit Tigers that year. On September 14, 1974, he made his MLB debut with the Tigers in a game against the [[New York Yankees]], where in one [[at bat]] he went hitless.<ref name="74log">{{cite web|title=Dan Meyer 1974 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=meyerda01&t=b&year=1974|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> He received his first hit on September 20, in a game against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]].<ref name=74log /> Meyer also hit two home runs in that game, the first coming in the third [[inning]] off of Brewers' [[starting pitcher|starter]] [[Bill Champion]], and the second coming Brewers' [[relief pitcher|reliever]] [[Bill Travers (baseball)|Bill Travers]] in the seventh inning.<ref name=74log /><ref>{{cite web|title=Sep 20, 1974, Tigers at Brewers Box Score and Play by Play|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/MIL/MIL197409200.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> In 13 games with Detroit that year, Meyer batted .200 with five runs scored, 10 hits, one double, one triple, three home runs, seven RBIs, and one stolen base. All of his 12 defensive games were played in [[left fielder|left field]].

In 1975, Meyer played his first full season at the major league level. He played left field and [[first baseman|first base]] in the field. During the fifth inning of a game against the [[Boston Red Sox]] on April 25, Meyer hit a home run to break up [[Luis Tiant]]'s [[perfect game]] bid.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lolich Outduels Boston's Tiant|date=26 April 1975|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fowsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9ssEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3125,4366845&dq=dan+meyer&hl=en|work=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> One day after hitting the game-winning home run for the Tigers against the Milwaukee Brewers on May 7, Meyer committed a throwing [[error (baseball)|error]] that let the deciding [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]]' run score.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paladino|first=Larry|date=9 May 1975|title=Meyer's Goof Costs Tigers a Ball Game|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YHgiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_KwFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1046,949975&dq=dan+meyer&hl=en|work=Associated Press|publisher=Argus-Press|accessdate=19 November 2010}}</ref> He batted .236 with 56 runs scored, 111 hits, 17 doubles, three triples, eight home runs, 47 RBIs, and eight stolen bases in 122 games played during the 1975 season. Meyer led the [[American League]] that year in [[at bats per strikeouts]] with 18.8, which was over four points more than [[Mickey Rivers]], who was second in the league in that statistic.<ref>{{cite web|title=1975 American League Batting Leaders|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1975-batting-leaders.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref>

Meyer played 105 games in 1976 for the Tigers. On the year, he batted .252 with 37 runs scored, 74 hits, eight doubles, four triples, two home runs, 16 RBIs, and 10 stolen bases. His batting average was the highest it would ever be as a Tigers player, despite the decline in at-bats (470 in 1975, 294 in 1976). During the season, Meyer played 47 games in left field, 19 at first base, and one in the [[designated hitter]] spot.

===Seattle Mariners===
During the [[1976 Major League Baseball expansion draft]], Meyer was selected by the [[Seattle Mariners]], who chose him ninth overall.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle, Toronto Go After Youth|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=svseAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jFEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3927,794117&dq=dan+meyer+mariners&hl=en|work=[[The Dispatch (Lexington)|The Dispatch]]|accessdate=20 November 2010|date=3 November 1976}}</ref> On June 9, 1977, in a game against the [[Minnesota Twins]], Meyer hit two home runs.<ref name="77log">{{cite web|title=Dan Meyer 1977 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=meyerda01&t=b&year=1977|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Meyer Belts 2 Home Runs For Seattle|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8cYxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0g0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5613,6143037&dq=dan+meyer&hl=en|work=[[Toledo Blade]]|accessdate=20 November 2010|date=10 July 1977}}</ref> In his first season with the Mariners, Meyer batted .273 with 75 runs scored, 159 hits, 24 doubles, four triples, 22 home runs, 90 RBIs, and 11 stolen bases in 159 games played. He led the American League with 159 defensive games at first base.<ref>{{cite web|title=1977 American League Fielding Leaders|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1977-fielding-leaders.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref> During the Mariners inaugural season, he led the team in hits and RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|title=1977 Seattle Mariners Batting, Pitching, & Fielding Statistics|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/SEA/1977.shtml|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref> Meyer also set multiple career highs in 1977 that would stand until the end of his professional tenure in games played, [[plate appearances]] (639), at bats (582), runs scored, hits, home runs, RBIs, [[base on balls|walks]] (43), [[strikeout]]s (51), [[on-base percentage]] (.320), and total bases (257).

In 1978, Meyer saw his offensive statistics decline. In 123 games played, he batted .227 with 38 runs scored, 101 hits, 18 doubles, one triple, eight home runs, 56 RBIs, and seven stolen bases. Defensively, he played 121 games at first base and two games in left field. Meyer was moved back to third base during the 1979 season, while also playing limited time at left field and first base. In June, while Meyer was having success at the plate, he attributed it to switching positions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meyer's hot, M's win|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Db40AAAAIBAJ&sjid=2YcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4134,8254558&dq=dan+meyer&hl=en|work=[[Tri-City Herald]]|accessdate=20 November 2010|date=26 June 1979}}</ref> On the season, Meyer batted .278 with 72 runs scored, 146 hits, 21 doubles, seven triples, 20 home runs, 74 RBIs, and 11 stolen bases in 144 games played.

During the 1980 season, Meyer batted .275 with 56 runs scored, 146 hits, 25 doubles, six triples, 11 home runs, 71 RBIs, and eight stolen bases in 146 games played for Seattle. Meyer spent his final season as a Mariners player in 1981, batting .262 with 26 runs scored, 66 hits, 10 doubles, one triple, three home runs, and 22 RBIs in 83 games played. Meyer saw his playing time decrease that season due to strained [[abdominal muscles]], which had him on the [[disabled list]] from the start of the season to April 15.<ref>{{cite web|title=M's reactivate  Danny Meyer|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-SMiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-IcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3124,6558134&dq=dan+meyer+disabled+list&hl=en|work=Tri-City Herald|accessdate=20 November 2010|date=April 15, 1981}}</ref>

===Oakland Athletics and later career===
In December 1981, the Seattle Mariners traded Meyer to the [[Oakland Athletics]] in exchange for [[Rich Bordi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sutcliffe Gets Wish; Traded To Cleveland|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GWEeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=eMgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2354,2475234&dq=dan+meyer&hl=en|work=Times Daily|accessdate=20 November 2010|date=10 December 1981}}</ref> In his first season with the Athletics, Meyer batted .240 with 28 runs scored, 92 hits, 17 doubles, three triples, eight home runs, and 59 RBIs in 120 games played. With Oakland that year, Meyer was primarily used as a first baseman in the field, but did see limited time in right field, and left field. He was also the designated hitter during 38 games. During the 1983 season, Meyer batted .189 with runs scored, 32 hits, nine doubles, one home run, and 13 RBIs in 69 games played.

In 1984, Meyer found himself starting the season in the minor league for the first time in ten years. With the [[Tacoma Tigers]] of the Triple-A [[Pacific Coast League]], Meyer batted .293 with 134 hits, 19 doubles, two triples, and seven home runs in 124 games played. Meyer was called-up to the majors in September.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dan Meyer 1984 Batting Gamelogs|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.cgi?id=meyerda01&t=b&year=1984|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref> As a member of the Athletics, Meyer batted .318 with one run scored, seven hits, three doubles, one triple, and four RBIs in 20 games played. After the season, he filed for [[free agent|free agency]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago's Sutcliffe files for free agency|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aMosAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pRMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4092,6039357&dq=dan+meyer&hl=en|work=[[Wilmington Morning Star]]|accessdate=20 November 2010|date=20 October 1984}}</ref>

On January 15, 1985, Meyer re-signed with the Athletics. With Oakland that year, Meyer went hitless in 12 at bats. He was released by the team on May 26. For the duration of the 1985 season, Meyer played with the Triple-A [[Nashville Sounds]], who were the minor league affiliates of the Detroit Tigers. With the Sounds that year, Meyer batted .225 with 36 hits, 13 doubles, one triple, and one home run in 51 games played. During the 1986 season, Meyer was absent from professional baseball. He resurfaced in 1987, playing three games with the Class-A [[San Jose Bees]] of the [[California League]].

